The principle is sufficiently clumsy ; the utility questionable, since nothing can be established by this process which may not be proved more simply in other ways. It may be observed also, that the objection which Lainbert urges, and with reason, against the conversion of the second and third figures, viz. that by conversion we often substitute an un— natural and indirect for a natural and direct predication, does not hold as regards the fourth. For, in the first three moods no conversion of premises is needed. By regarding the first stated as the minor, the second as the major, we obtain a much more natural conclusion in the first figure. Fesapo and Fresison establish eoecepstons, and therefore, on Lambert’s theory, should more naturally fall into the third figure. The whole distinction, however, between natural and unnatural predication relates to the matter, not to the form of the thought.
